{
  "id": "jsonbored_gittensory_228",
  "repo_name": "jsonbored/gittensory",
  "repo_url": "https://github.com/jsonbored/gittensory",
  "base_commit": "d41591a7c763762e122d805e0f29de73c8a616f1",
  "pr_number": 228,
  "issue_number": 227,
  "issue_title": "[Bug]: `buildObservedPullRequestScenarios` classifies open PRs stale-before-blocked, inverting the authoritative `classifyOpenPullRequest` order and relieving open-PR pressure for PRs that are actually blocked",
  "issue_body": "## Summary\n\nIn `src/signals/local-branch.ts`, `buildObservedPullRequestScenarios` classifies each open PR by checking **stale before blocked**:\n\n```ts\n// src/signals/local-branch.ts:567-575\nif (isStaleOpenPr(pr, args.nowMs)) {   // stale checked FIRST\n  stale += 1;\n  continue;\n}\nif (isBlockedOpenPr(pr)) {             // blocked only reached if NOT stale\n  blocked += 1;\n  continue;\n}\nif (isApprovedOrMergeableOpenPr(pr)) approvedOrMergeable += 1;\n```\n\n`isStaleOpenPr` (no update in \u226514 days) and `isBlockedOpenPr` (`reviewDecision === \"changes_requested\"` or a bad `mergeableState`) are **independent** predicates (`local-branch.ts` helper defs), so a PR can satisfy both. When it does, the stale branch short-circuits and the PR is counted as `stale`.\n\nThis inverts the precedence used by the **authoritative** open-PR classifier, `classifyOpenPullRequest`, which checks **blocked before stale**:\n\n```ts\n// src/scoring/pending-pr-scenarios.ts:193-200  (the correct reference)\nif (changeRequestCount > 0 || checkFailureCount > 0 || approvalCount === 0) {\n  return { ... classification: \"blocked\", ... };          // blocked FIRST\n}\nif (ageDays >= STALE_DAYS) {                                // STALE_DAYS = 14\n  return { ... classification: \"stale_likely_close\", ... }; // stale only if not blocked\n}\n```\n\nA PR that is both changes-requested **and** untouched for \u226514 days is `blocked` under the authoritative path but `stale` here.\n\n## Why the inversion changes the score (asymmetric downstream use)\n\nThe two buckets are **not** treated symmetrically downstream. `stale` is subtracted from open-PR pressure; `blocked` is not:\n\n```ts\n// src/signals/local-branch.ts:421-425 \u2014 observed scenarios become score inputs\nobservedApprovedPrCount: args.observedPullRequestScenarios.approvedOrMergeable,\nobservedStalePrCount:    args.observedPullRequestScenarios.stale,\nobservedBlockedPrCount:  args.observedPullRequestScenarios.blocked,\n```\n\n```ts\n// src/scoring/preview.ts\nconst observedStaleCloseCount = nonNegative(input.observedStalePrCount);          // :353\nconst combinedPendingCount = userPendingCount + observedApprovedCount + observedStaleCloseCount; // :355  -> bestReasonableCase (:389)\nconst afterStaleInput = { ...input, openPrCount: Math.max(0, current.gates.openPrCount - observedStaleCloseCount) }; // :370-372  -> afterStalePrsClose\n...\n// observedBlockedPrCount only produces a NOTE, never subtracted:\n...(nonNegative(input.observedBlockedPrCount) > 0 ? [`${...} blocked PR(s) were excluded from likely-to-land projections.`] : []), // :466\n```\n\nSo a PR counted as `stale` is **subtracted** from the projected open-PR count in the `afterStalePrsClose` and `bestReasonableCase` scenarios (modeled as \"will close, freeing a slot\"), whereas a PR counted as `blocked` correctly **stays** as open-PR pressure. Mis-routing a blocked PR into `stale` therefore over-relieves the open-PR gate.\n\n## Failure mode (concrete example)\n\nA contributor has `openPrCount = 3`. One of those open PRs has `reviewDecision = \"changes_requested\"` and was last updated 20 days ago; the other two are unremarkable. `totalTokenScore = 90` \u2192 `openPrThreshold = 2 + floor(90/300) = 2`.\n\n- **Current (stale-first):** the changes-requested PR is counted as `stale` \u2192 `observedStalePrCount = 1`. `afterStalePrsClose` open-PR count = `3 \u2212 1 = 2` \u2192 `2 <= 2` \u2192 `openPrMultiplier = 1` \u2192 the scenario reports a **full positive score** (\"wait for the stale PR to close and you're scoreable\").\n- **Correct (blocked-first, per `classifyOpenPullRequest`):** the PR is `blocked` \u2192 `observedStalePrCount = 0`, `observedBlockedPrCount = 1`. `afterStalePrsClose` open-PR count = `3 \u2212 0 = 3` \u2192 `3 <= 2` is false \u2192 `openPrMultiplier = 0` \u2192 the scenario stays **0** (gate still blocked).\n\nA PR that is blocked on the author (changes requested) is optimistically modeled as \"likely to close on its own and free up a slot,\" flipping the open-PR gate and inflating the projected score. The same `observedStaleCloseCount` also feeds `bestReasonableCase` (`preview.ts:389`).\n\n## Downstream impact\n\n- Inflated `afterStalePrsClose` and `bestReasonableCase` effective scores, and a wrong `scoreabilityStatus` (`conditionally_scoreable` where it should stay `blocked`).\n- A spurious \"wait for stale PRs to close / cleanup-first\" recommendation (`local-branch.ts:591` note) for PRs that are actually blocked on the author and need the author to act, not time to pass.\n- Two classifiers of the same concept (which open PRs leave the queue) disagree on the same input, so the projection a contributor sees depends on which path produced it.\n\n## Steps to reproduce\n\n1. Build a local-branch analysis (or call `buildObservedPullRequestScenarios`) for a contributor whose open PRs include one with `reviewDecision: \"changes_requested\"` and `updatedAt` \u2265 14 days in the past.\n2. Inspect the resulting `observedStalePrCount` / `observedBlockedPrCount` (or the `afterStalePrsClose` scenario in the score preview).\n3. Observe the PR counted as `stale` (and subtracted from open-PR pressure) instead of `blocked`.\n\n## Expected behavior\n\nOpen-PR classification checks **blocked before stale**, matching `classifyOpenPullRequest` (`pending-pr-scenarios.ts:193-200`): a changes-requested / failing-checks PR is `blocked` regardless of age, so it is never optimistically modeled as closing.\n\n## Actual behavior\n\n`buildObservedPullRequestScenarios` checks stale before blocked, so a changes-requested-and-stale PR is counted as `stale` and subtracted from projected open-PR pressure, inflating the `afterStalePrsClose`/`bestReasonableCase` scenarios.\n\n## Suggested fix\n\n- Reorder the checks in `buildObservedPullRequestScenarios` (`local-branch.ts:567-575`) so `isBlockedOpenPr` is tested **before** `isStaleOpenPr`, mirroring the authoritative precedence in `classifyOpenPullRequest`:\n\n  ```ts\n  if (isBlockedOpenPr(pr)) { blocked += 1; continue; }\n  if (isStaleOpenPr(pr, args.nowMs)) { stale += 1; continue; }\n  if (isApprovedOrMergeableOpenPr(pr)) approvedOrMergeable += 1;\n  ```\n\n  (Consider sharing a single classification helper between the two paths so they cannot drift again.)\n\n- Add fail-on-revert coverage: an open PR with `reviewDecision: \"changes_requested\"` and `updatedAt` 20 days old must be counted as `blocked` (not `stale`), and the `afterStalePrsClose` scenario must not subtract it from `openPrCount`. The existing observed-scenario tests use PRs that are stale **or** blocked but not both, so they ratify the inverted order rather than catching it.",
  "merged_at": "2026-06-02T04:31:28.000Z",
